The Most Dangerous Boston Neighborhoods¶

by Medha Kuruganti

Motivation¶

When you look up the most dangerous neighborhoods in Boston, you'll often find the same couple of options: Roxbury, Mattapan, and Dorchester. And as someone from Massachsuetts, this is consistent with what people generally believe. Growing up, I was always told that these areas were extremely dangerous, and I should ultimately avoid them as much as possible. Now, part of me always believed that some of this had to do with the racial demographics of these neighborhoods. Overall, Massachusetts is predominantly white. However, as the state capital, Boston's demographics tend to vary more than the suburbs. According to the Massachusetts Census, 44.7% of Boston's population is White, while 24.2% is Black, 9.8% is Asian, and 19.5% is Hispanic/Latino. At the same time, as of 2019, the demographics in the 3 most dangerous neighborhoods in Boston are as follows:

  • Roxbury: 50.3% Black, 30.7% Hispanic, 11% White, 3.5% Asian
  • Mattapan: 74.4% Black, 14.1% Hispanic, 6% White, 1.9% Asian
  • Dorchester: 44% Black, 19.9% Hispanic, 22.3% White, 9.9% Asian

In all 3 of these neighborhoods, we can see that there are more people of color, and specifically, more Black and Hispanic populations than White populations in these neighborhoods. But, now that I am much older, I do not want racial biases to influence my opinions on the danger levels of the neighborhoods in my favorite city. Thus, I will be analyzing the danger levels of the major Boston neighborhoods to determine which ones truly are the most dangerous.

After I explore the ways in which Boston neighborhoods are dangerous, I will look to see if there is a relationship between the dangerousness of a neighborhood and whether or not the majority of the population is POC or not. I am not doing this analysis to encourage the belief that majority POC neighborhoods are possibly more dangerous. I am doing this analysis to see if, first, there is even any type of relationship between race and danger (although, I do not believe there is), and second, to emphasize that possible high rates of crime in majority POC neighborhoods are a result of bad infrastructure and lack of societal aid.

I chose to analyze the crime data in Boston neighborhoods. Here, I got all the crime incident reports in 2022 in Boston (based on district/location). I dropped all rows with missing data (e.g., latitudes and longitudes that were set to (0,0), districts that were not in Boston, and NaN values. I also dropped columns that were not relevant to any analysis I performed. The only columns from this dataset that I used were: OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION and DISTRICT.

With this dataset, I created 2 different dataframes for my analyses and hypotheses testing. These dataframes were divided by the dataset's OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION and SHOOTING columns.

Now that I have the locations of each of these districts, I will be grouping the data by levels of danger. In this case, crimes like shootings, murders, and manslaughter would be the highest crimes, while vandalism and shoplifting would be the lowest crimes. These levels were determined by my personal opinions of these crimes and how horrible they are.

When looking at the danger levels, it is important to note that Danger Level 1 is the least dangerous while Danger Level 5 is the most dangerous. As mentioned before, these levels were determined by my own opinions and what society seemingly believes regarding danger levels. The levels are determined as follows:

  • Danger Level 1: crimes related to high noise levels, vandalism/graffiti, public disputes (non-dangerous), low violations (license, evading fare, trespassing, etc)
  • Danger Level 2: crimes related to motor vehicle accidents/property damage
  • Danger Level 3: crimes related robbery, embezzlement, and fraud
  • Danger Level 4: crimes related to bodily harm (i.e., threats, harrassment, abuse, kidnapping, assault)
  • Danger Level 5: crimes related to illegal drug and alcohol violations and death (i.e., bombs/weapons, murder/manslaughter)
    • It could be argued that illegal drug and alcohol violations should not belong in this level, but based on the way police/society treats this, I kept it in this category. From a quick glance, it does not seem like these will overpower the category and make neighborhoods have high Danger Level 5 scores; however, it is a possibility that I did not account for.

Additionally, I dropped rows that did not seem like crimes, or that did not give sufficient information for what crime occured. Many of these crimes were accidents in which the person themselves was injured or suffered, were not crimes, were deaths (but the death either was not a crime or the cause was not mentioned), there were no injuries/consequences, or the crime was resolved by the time it was recorded. These were labeled as NaN values and then dropped. These included:

  • INVESTIGATE PERSON
  • INVESTIGATE PROPERTY
  • AIRCRAFT INCIDENTS
  • ANIMAL INCIDENTS (DOG BITES, LOST DOG, ETC)
  • TOWED MOTOR VEHICLE
  • SICK ASSIST
  • INJURY BICYCLE NO M/V INVOLVED
  • M/V ACCIDENT - OTHER
  • PROPERTY - FOUND

  • SICK/INJURED/MEDICAL - PERSON
  • PROPERTY - STOLEN THEN RECOVERED
  • WARRANT ARREST - OUTSIDE OF BOSTON WARRANT

  • MISSING PERSON - LOCATED

import re

danger_lev = []

for idx, row in crime_table.iterrows():
    
    # danger level 1
    if (row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "AFFRAY" or row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VERBAL DISPUTE" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "TRESPASSING" or row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VANDALISM" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VIOLATION - CITY ORDINANCE" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "PROPERTY - ACCIDENTAL DAMAGE" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "NOISY PARTY/RADIO-NO ARREST" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "DISTURBING THE PEACE/ DISORDERLY CONDUCT/ GATHERING CAUSING ANNOYANCE/ NOISY PAR" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V PLATES - LOST" or row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "EVADING FARE" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "GRAFFITI" or row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VAL - OPERATING AFTER REV/SUSP." or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VAL - VIOLATION OF AUTO LAW" or row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "AFFRAY" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "LICENSE PREMISE VIOLATION" or 
        row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "VAL - OPERATING W/O AUTHORIZATION LAWFUL"):
        danger_lev.append(1)
    
    # danger level 2
    elif (row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V - LEAVING SCENE - PROPERTY DAMAGE" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V ACCIDENT - OTHER CITY VEHICLE" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V ACCIDENT - PROPERTY DAMAGE" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V ACCIDENT - POLICE VEHICLE"):
        danger_lev.append(2)
    
    # danger level 3
    elif re.match(r"LARCENY ", row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"]):
        danger_lev.append(3)
    
    elif re.match(r"AUTO THEFT", row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"]):
        danger_lev.append(3)
   
    elif re.match(r"FRAUD - ", row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"]):
        danger_lev.append(3)
    
    # danger level 4
    elif (row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "ROBBERY" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "BREAKING AND ENTERING (B&E) MOTOR VEHICLE (NO PROPERTY STOLEN)" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "BURGLARY - COMMERICAL" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "FORGERY / COUNTERFEITING" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "EXTORTION OR BLACKMAIL" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "EMBEZZLEMENT" or 
          row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "POSSESSION OF BURGLARIOUS TOOLS"):
        danger_lev.append(3)
    
    elif re.match(r"ASSAULT - ", row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"]):
        danger_lev.append(4)
    
    elif (row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "THREATS TO DO BODILY HARM" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "M/V ACCIDENT - INVOLVING PEDESTRIAN - INJURY" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "HARASSMENT/ CRIMINAL HARASSMENT" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "ANIMAL ABUSE" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "KIDNAPPING/CUSTODIAL KIDNAPPING/ ABDUCTION" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "MISSING PERSON"):
        danger_lev.append(4)
     
    # danger level 5
    elif (row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "DRUGS - POSSESSION/ SALE/ MANUFACTURING/ USE" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "BALLISTICS EVIDENCE/FOUND" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "FIREARM/WEAPON - FOUND OR CONFISCATED" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "OPERATING UNDER THE INFLUENCE (OUI) ALCOHOL" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "BOMB THREAT" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "MURDER, NON-NEGLIGENT MANSLAUGHTER" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "EXPLOSIVES - TURNED IN OR FOUND" or 
         row["OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION"] == "LIQUOR LAW VIOLATION"):
        danger_lev.append(5)
    
    # any other crime will be labeled as NaN
    else:
        danger_lev.append(np.nan)

crime_table["DANGER LEVEL"] = danger_lev
crime_table.head()

Exploratory Analysis¶

In this part of the project, I will be analyzing how dangerous each of the Boston neighborhoods are. This will be done in 3 different ways:

  1. Determine which neighborhoods are the most dangerous by their relative recorded crime reports to each other.
  2. Determine which neighborhoods are the most dangerous by the danger levels.
  3. Determine which neighborhoods are the most dangerous based on the number of shootings (which would be similar to having a danger level of 5 or higher).

Part 1: Danger by relative recorded crime reports¶

In this section, I will get the total crime reports (regardless of danger level) for each of the neighborhoods. Since reports of shootings and offense descriptions can both exist for a crime, I do not count them separately. Once I get the total counts for each neighborhood, I create a pie chart to compare the relative amount of crime that occurs in each neighborhood.

In [12]:

According to this plot, the neighborhoods with the top crime reports are the South End (14.7%), Dorchester (14.0%), and Roxbury (13.0%). This is in comparison to the total crime in Boston. This also only considers the crime reports that I considered crimes previously. As a result, these numbers are biased as to what I considered sufficient enough information for a crime or that I determined to be a crime.

According to the Motivation section, I showed that the top most dangerous neighborhoods in Boston are Roxbury, Mattapan, and Dorchester. After parsing the data based on what I perceived to be possible crimes, we can see that the only neighborhood that satisfies the top most dangerous neighborhood list is Dorchester. Roxbury, with 12.9% of Boston crime, had the 4th most crimes reported, and Mattapan had the 6th most crimes reported.

While I am unsure whether or not the data would be different had I included all of the crimes, we can see that there is a discrepancy here between what the Internet claims are the most dangerous neighborhoods and what my analysis shows. If I consider danger by the number of crimes that occur, then the South End and Dorchester should be the most dangerous cities with Roxbury right behind them. But while we see Dorchester and Roxbury being dangerous neighborhoods, the South End is not necessarily known for its high crime levels.

Because of this discrepancy, I now look at the relative dangers of each of these neighborhood to see if I get different results. Reports (such as this one) have shown that the South End does have dangerous areas, but has relatively low violent crime. As a result, I will also look at the relative number of crimes and their danger levels to see if neighborhoods with more crime have less dangerous crimes.

Part 2: Danger based on danger levels¶

In this section, I analyze how dangerous each neighborhood is based on which level of crime is the most prevalent in the neighborhood. This is done by grouping the data by neighborhood and danger level, looking at their relative crimes through a bar graph and looking at their relative crimes through a pie chart for each neighborhood.

First, I look at the mean danger levels for each neighborhood. This gives us a very basic idea of how dangerous each neighborhood is. From these values, we can see which neighborhoods may have the highest danger levels.

From the above graphs, we get the following results for the highest percentage of crime for each level of danger:

  • Danger Level 3: South End (46.9%), West Roxbury (39.2%), Downtown (38.2%)

Based on this data, we can see that Mattapan, Downtown, South Boston, and Jamaica Plain seem to be the most dangerous neighborhoods, based on their relative danger levels of crime. This is because they have the highest percentage of danger level 5 and danger level 4 crimes, where levels 5 and 4 refer to crimes that result in (the threat of) bodily harm and the posession of illegal/dangerous objects (i.e., drugs, weapons). These findings are consistent with the mean danger levels of the neighborhoods that I initially explored.

nhoods = df["NEIGHBORHOOD"].unique()

num_shootings = [0]*12
counter = 0

# count the number of shootings per neighborhood (shootings are defined as "1")
for n in nhoods:
    num_shoot = 0
    
    for idx, row in df[df["NEIGHBORHOOD"] == n].iterrows():
        if row["SHOOTING"] != 0:
            num_shoot += 1
    
    num_shootings[counter] = num_shoot
    counter += 1
    
shooting_table["SHOOTINGS"] = num_shootings

# sort the dataframe by max number of shootings to see which neighborhoods have most
shooting_table.sort_values(by=["SHOOTINGS"], ascending=False)

Hypothesis Testing¶

Now that I have determined which neighborhoods are the most dangerous based on each analysis method, let's see if there is a relationship between racial demographics and high crime for each of the methods.

While I do not believe high danger and crime is a result of mainly POC neighborhoods, nor do I think that the reason why mainly POC neighborhoods may have high crime rates is because the neighborhoods' make-ups are predominantly POC (this ultimately is a result of a lack of societal aid), I do think it is important to see if there even is a relationship. If there is a relationship (i.e., there is higher crime in POC neighborhoods), then that means our society needs to invest more in these neighborhoods and provide aid to them in ways they need it. If not, then there's no reason for these biases to exist - although it is important to note that we should all be dispelling these biases regardless of the answer.

In the following graphs, we label majority POC neighborhoods in red, and majority White neighborhoods in black. The majority POC neighborhoods are: Dorchester, Roxbury, Mattapan, East Boston, and Hyde Park. The majority White neighborhoods are: the South End, Downtown, South Boston, Brighton, Jamaica Plain, West Roxbury, and Charlestown.

# plot linear regression model to see if there is a reltionship between crime and racial demographics
def linreg_plot(df, x, y, title):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    fig = sns.regplot(df[x], df[y])
    plt.title(title)
    
    # label majority POC neighborhoods red, and majority White black
    for idx, row in df.iterrows():
        if float(row["POC"]) > float(row["White"]):
            c = "red"
        else:
            c = "black"
        
        ax.annotate(row["NEIGHBORHOOD"], (df[x][idx],df[y][idx]), color=c)

Danger Level 1¶

While there is not an obvious relatioship between the number of Danger Level 1 crimes and a neighborhood having a majority POC make-up, there is a slight relationship. The South End and Downtown seem to be outliers in this linear regression model, but Roxbury, Dorchester, and Mattapan do follow the linear regression model, showing more Danger Level 1 crimes than the other majority White neighborhoods.

In this analysis, it is important to consider what Danger Level 1 entails. These are crimes that are not very dangerous at all: loud noises, slight altercations, etc. There are studies/articles (e.g, this one) that have shown that more POC areas have more noise, and White neighbors are more likely to call the police on them. So, in this case, although there may be a relationship between race and more Danger Level 1 crimes, this could be a result of societal biases.

Danger Level 2¶

For Danger Level 2, we see a similar, but maybe more defined, relationship between majority POC neighborhoods and the amount of Danger Level 2 crimes. Once again, these crimes are focused on motorvehicle accidents, so these are not necessarily crimes in the same way as other more dangerous crimes. While I have not done an analysis on it, this may just be a result of traffic or bad roads.

Danger Level 3¶

The Danger Level 3 graph shows no siginificant relationship between the racial make-up of a neighborhood and the amount of Danger Level 3 crimes. These are crimes related to fraud, larceny, embezzlement, and burglary. This refutes the belief that majority POC neighborhoods are mroe likely to be thiefs, and is a good example of why stores need not lock up products meant for Black populations (not that there was ever a reason, but this shows that there is no reason).

Danger Level 4¶

The Danger Level 4 graph also shows no significant relationship between the racial make-up of a neighborhood and the amount of Danger Level 4 crimes. While Roxbury and Dorchester have high amounts of Danger Level 4 crimes, so do Downtown and the South End. These crimes are a bit more agressive, dealing with threats to bodily harm, kidnapping, assault, etc. But according to this regression analysis, these crimes exist almost equally in all of the neighborhoods.

Danger Level 5¶

The Danger Level 5 graph also doesn't truly show a relationship between the racial make-up of a neighborhood and the amount of Danger Level 5 crimes There does seem to be some type of relationship, but the South End and Downtown are outliers that score high on the count rate. This once again shows that majority POC neighborhoods are not the only ones with high rates of dangerous crime.

Insights¶

From this analysis, I would agree that Roxbury, Mattapan, and Dorchester are dangerous neighborhoods in Boston, but based on my analysis, so are the South End and Downtown. Based on the relativity of crime seen in the Exploratory Analysis section (through the total crime percentages and number of shootings) and the Hypothesis Testing section, it was clear that the three neighborhoods are often found for having quite a lot of crime. It is important to also note that Downtown and the South End often also showed up as high crime neighborhoods. While, as someone from Massachsuetts, I am not entirely surprised about the South End, I am slightly (but not completely) surprised that Downtown often made the top of the list. Simulateneously, while I argue that the South End and Downtown are just as dnagerous, Roxbury, Mattapan, and Dorchester have the most amount of shootings by a significant amount, so I will also argue that because of their high shooting rates, they are more dangerous than Downtown and the South End.

Beyond looking at the amount of crime in each neighborhood, it is also important to consider what leads to these crimes. In general, Boston has had a terrible relationship with individuals of color - and, especially, Black populations. Crime does lead to danger, but if the city of Boston and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts cannot see that high crime rates show a failure of society and the government to help these populations, then these neighborhoods will continue to have crime rates and will never be "safe". Additionally, it is important to consider how the gentrification of some of these neighborhoods leads to more crime reports because populations that think they are better move into these areas and call the police more often on their neighbors (for things that may not be actual crimes). Often, gentrification leads to more racial profiling, which could be cause for more crime reports - and supposedly more crimes. Finally, it's also important to consider if police are more often stationed in the areas that have been shown to have higher crime rates. If there is more policing in a neighborhood - and there often is more policing in majority POC areas - then of course the neighborhood will have more crime reports, even if they do not necessarily have more crime.

Overall, this analysis has shown that while racial make-up does not actually have much of a relationship with crime in Boston neighborhoods, the neighborhoods with the most crime reported were in the majority POC neighborhoods of Mattapan, Dorchester, and Roxbury. But there was also high crime in Downtown and the South End. What this shows us is that neighborhoods of any racial make-up may have high rates of crime, but we must make sure to invest in those neighborhoods that have more crime - and this does not mean investing in more police - to create environments that sustain and aid these populations as this will reduce crime.
